Good point! I’m thinking of adding a CLI with clap-rs; it seems the most idiomatic way to do that. Here’s an example of how I could parse args:

```rust
fn main() {
    let matches = Command::new("RustScrum")
        .version("0.1")
        .author("Me")
        .about("Rusty Scrum CLI tool")
        .arg(
            Arg::with_name("status")
                .short('s')
                .long("status")
                .help("Print sprint status")
        )
        .get_matches();

    if matches.is_present("status") {
        println!("Sprint status is Planned");
    }
}
```
What do you think of that?

Pretty straightforward. But remember to handle errors gracefully—what happens if the sprint isn’t found? Wrap your CLI logic in a `Result` and return user-friendly messages:

```rust
if !matches.is_present("status") {
    eprintln!("Error: Missing command");
    std::process::exit(1);
}
```
